By the way, notice the naming in the code here. Following the Java naming conventions makes code easier to read. For example, variables and methods both start with a lowercase letter. So, `int AbsC;` should be `int absC;`. And `UpdateBoard()` should be `updateBoard()`. 

## OOP with multiple methods makes code easier to comprehend

Hopefully you can see how using multiple methods and OOP makes this code much easier to read and comprehend. OOP was invented to make life easier for human programmers, not for the benefit of computer machines.

 - A programmer looking at this class can glance at the member fields to see the main idea of the class: Holding a certain number of slots. 
 - Then a glance at the constructor reveals the nature of the slots, defaulting to a series of numbers. 
 - And then looking at the `main` shows how our intention is to alter the board by randomizing the values of those slots. 

Tip: [IDE][4]s provide a “structure” panel to expose and navigate these methods, for quick review by a programmer.


